Kantorowicz in his seminal work from 1957, The King’s Two Bodies. On the basis of both textual self-presentations and visual representations a gradual transformation of the queen appears: A sacred/providential figure in medieval and early modern period, an ideal bourgeois wife during the late-18th and 19th Centuries, and a star-like (re-) presentation of royalty during the past century. Twentieth-century mass media has produced the celebrity and film star queens personified by the contested and enigmatic Nefertiti of ancient Egypt, the mysterious Elizabeth (Sisi) of Austria, Grace Kelly as Queen of both Hollywood and Monaco and Romy Schneider as the invented Empress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCourts and courtiersxHistory. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspects. 0aMonarchyxHistory. 0aQueens. 0aSex rolexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Women .2bisacsh1 aBepler, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreger, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrice, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrye, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohlrausch, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontrose, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulte, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulte, Regina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchwarzenbach, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSykora, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVogel, Juliane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeil, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/